<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-018-366  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 018 366.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC Professional  Oct 1989 v8 n11 p36(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Put more fiber in your network. (understanding and preparing forFiber Distributed Data Interface networks)(includes a relatedarticle on Digital Equipment Corp's FDDI activities)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hancock, Bill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical fiber-based Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI)technology is useful for fast, highly available backbone networks;but the high cost of FDDI networks and the low loads on currentcopper-based networks keep FDDI systems from being cost-effectivefor most existing local area network (LAN) applications.andO;Advantages of FDDI technology include high speed, relative noiseimmunity, ease of upgrade, electrically isolated environment, andrapid interconnection of and conversion between dissimilar networktechnologies.andP;  FDDI technology is of particular use in connectingmany distant LANs (to 100Km distance) and in replacingconventional token ring architectures (FDDI is a dual,counter-rotating token ring network).andP;  Differences between FDDIand conventional token-ring LANs are detailed.andP;  Fiber materialsand difficulties in configuring FDDI networks are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardTechnologySystem DesignCost Benefit AnalysisComparisonApplicationsFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   FDDI group codes. (table)FDDI frame format. (chart)FDDI general topology. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>